    bio: "Cyrus II of Persia, known to history as Cyrus the Great, founded the Achaemenid Empire — the largest empire the world had yet seen — through a combination of military genius and a political philosophy strikingly ahead of its time. Born around 600 BC in the region of Anshan in modern Iran, he rose from a minor vassal king to overthrow the Median Empire, then the Lydian Kingdom of the legendary Croesus, and finally the ancient city of Babylon, all within roughly two decades. His campaigns were remarkable not only for their speed but for their consistent leniency: Cyrus made a habit of sparing defeated rulers, preserving local customs, and presenting himself as a legitimate heir to conquered traditions rather than a foreign conqueror.\n\nHis most celebrated act was the liberation of the Jews held in Babylonian captivity. After taking Babylon in 539 BC, Cyrus issued an edict — recorded on the famous Cyrus Cylinder, now in the British Museum — allowing exiled peoples to return to their homelands and rebuild their temples. The Hebrew Bible refers to him as a messiah, one of only two non-Israelites given that designation, and his name appears more than twenty times across the Old Testament. Modern scholars debate how much of his tolerance was genuine enlightenment versus shrewd imperial management, but the practical effect was an empire bound together by consent and cultural accommodation as much as military force.\n\nCyrus died around 530 BC, reportedly in battle against the Massagetae tribe northeast of the Caspian Sea. His tomb at Pasargadae — a simple, elegant stone structure on a stepped plinth — survived the centuries and was revered by Alexander the Great, who reportedly wept when he found it vandalized and ordered its restoration. The principles Cyrus embedded in Persian governance, religious tolerance, administrative delegation, and the infrastructure of the Royal Road, shaped every empire that followed him, earning him a reputation as the founder not just of a dynasty but of a new idea of what imperial rule could be."
